01:03.000 --> 01:12.280
Yeah, I realize you'd done those. I was sort of getting at those sort of a
series kind of show where you had to write something on cue. Well, I tried never

01:12.280 --> 01:24.000
to do that anyway. I had a very friendly relationship with Alfred Hitchcock and
all of his partners there, Joan Harrison and Norman Lloyd. and I'd go out and

01:24.000 --> 01:34.300
have a casual lunch, tell them an idea. They'd OK it. I'd go home and write it
and come back with a finished script, and we'd have another lunch. If they could

01:34.300 --> 01:42.940
argue me into any changes, I'd make them, and if I could argue them into the
logic of my situation, it stayed the way it was. So it was a very amiable, very

01:42.940 --> 01:54.120
friendly thing. I never did a lot of scripts. I wouldn't let myself get bullied
into being a full-time writer because no one remembers who writes scripts for

01:54.120 --> 02:06.520
television anyway. Were any of those things you did for those shows based on
your own stories? Most of them were. I did three one-hour shows for Hitchcock

02:06.520 --> 02:19.760
for his big one-hour series, and then I did eight or nine scripts, maybe 10 or
12 for the half-hour series, and all but one of those were my own stories. .

