02:59.540 --> 03:13.260
You're such a lover of books and so forth. I wonder how you give so much energy
to the visual arts. Well, I grew up with all these loves. If I have any capacity

03:13.260 --> 03:22.680
at all it's to be in love in six or seven different ways. So I've always been
madly in love with motion pictures. My mother was a fiend for them and took me

03:22.680 --> 03:36.680
to see hundreds of films from the age of when I was two until up until I was 10,
11, or 12. So that never left me, and I think I'm very fortunate to have a great

03:36.680 --> 03:46.820
love of films, a great love of libraries and books, a great love of radio, and
the famous people in radio. When I came west to live in Los Angeles, I headed

03:46.820 --> 03:58.660
downtown immediately and got to know all the people on an old radio broadcast
called Hollywood Hotel. And L sampler Parsons became a friend to this 13, 14

03:58.660 --> 04:12.440
-year-old boy. And I knew Burns and Allen during those years of 1934, 35, 36. I
wrote scripts for them every week and added them in. and, of course, I doubt if

04:12.440 --> 04:23.040
they even read them, but they pretended that they did, and they were very kind
to me, and then I was in love with Orson Welles when he came on the scene in

04:23.040 --> 04:33.680
radio, and Suspense, and Norman Corwin, who became my friend when I was 27 years
old. So I grew up then with a love of libraries, a love of radio, a love of

04:33.680 --> 04:46.020
films, and I think I'm very lucky that I've been able to work in all of these
different mediums and do rather well in each one of them. How many of your plays

04:46.020 --> 04:59.340
have been performed? Oh, I would say somewhere around 14 or 15 of them. Most of
them I've produced myself. Dandelion Wine here on the coast recently, back east

04:59.340 --> 05:10.240
a few years ago. The Martian Chronicles, which I produced here at a small
theater. Fahrenheit 451 two years ago, which turned out very well. A wonderful

05:10.240 --> 05:22.640
ice cream suit, then six or seven of my one-act plays. I've had The Anthem
Sprinters, which is all of my Irish experiences. So I've had a lot of fun with

05:22.640 --> 05:31.420
it, and I've made a lot of friends among actors. I've worked with a lot of good
people, including James Whitmore, who appeared in my first one-act play here,

05:31.620 --> 05:36.020
and had a benefit for the United Nations about 23 years ago.

