08:21.980 --> 08:32.220
Okay, you've written novels, short stories, poems, plays, operas, scripts, Is
there anything you haven't tried? I can't think of anything offhand now that I'm

08:32.220 --> 08:43.500
working on this libretto for this opera. That sort of rounds out the list. I'm
working on a detective murder mystery novel now which I've never done before. So

08:43.500 --> 08:55.200
it's a change for me in the novel form. I've been a great lover and admirer of
Dashiell Hammett and Raymond Chandler for the last 40 years or so. and always

08:55.200 --> 09:04.560
wanted to do something in that field. But I was afraid to do it because I wasn't
well enough educated even though I'd read hundreds of novels in the field when I

09:04.560 --> 09:13.760
was younger. It didn't seem to get into my bloodstream. But now I think I'm old
enough and I hope I've learned my lessons and when the novel comes out people

09:13.760 --> 09:24.420
will agree that it's at least an agreeable competitor in the field. Do you have
any date when that might come out? No, I would say about a year from now. It's

09:24.420 --> 09:33.720
right up close to being finished. I've been working on it seven or eight years.
But you never know. I might finish it all in one week in the next week or two.

09:34.020 --> 09:40.000
And, again, I may drag on for another six months. I'm not in charge. I don't
make the decisions.

09:42.520 --> 09:53.500
Okay. You're obviously extremely hard to categorize or to pinpoint. What do you
think? what do you think or how do you respond when you're categorized or called

09:53.500 --> 10:01.720
a science fiction writer. Does that bother you? Well, it can. Depends on how
it's used. Some people use it with prejudice. There are still some librarians in

10:01.720 --> 10:10.700
the country, there's still some critics, there's still some teachers who think
that science fiction isn't worth bothering with, and of course that drives me

10:10.700 --> 10:22.140
wild. So their opinion actually irritates me, because to me, it's the central
fiction of our time. We are a science-oriented, technologically oriented people

10:22.140 --> 10:32.240
and there's nothing else to write about except human beings in some sort of
relationship with their ideas, with their machineries, with their technologies.

10:32.980 --> 10:43.440
All the major problems of our time right now are technological, scientific,
moral problems. What do you do with the automobile? What do you do with nuclear

10:43.440 --> 10:55.620
power? What do you do with cloning? What do you do with DNA experimentation? All
these problems that arise as soon as you invent something new. So all of our

10:55.620 --> 11:07.560
major problems right now, you can't name one that's not connected to a machine
somewhere down the line. You see no opposition or antagonism, do you, between

11:07.560 --> 11:18.120
the arts and the sciences? There shouldn't be. I mean, after all, especially in
science fiction, were cooperating to give scientists ideas so that they can

11:18.120 --> 11:30.140
create new ways of living. Without the creative thought of the poet, the
filmmaker, the novelist of 100 years ago, we wouldn't be on the moon. We're on

11:30.140 --> 11:41.480
the moon at this very moment because Jules Verne put us there first. Okay,
excellent. I guess you wouldn't agree with what Plato had to say in his Republic

11:41.480 --> 11:50.860
about the danger of imaginative literature then? Well, there's always been bad
talk among intellectuals who don't stop and think what they're saying. It's a

11:50.860 --> 12:01.520
very dumb remark. I mean, if you don't have an imagination, you can't survive.
If you don't have some sort of creative instinct in you, how do you think people

12:01.520 --> 12:11.060
survive Buchenwald? Those who survive survive it with their imagination. A lot
of them were able to imagine at times for a little while they were somewhere

12:11.060 --> 12:21.040
else. If you're in a jail, if people are dying all around you, you damn well
better have the power of imagination so that you can imagine a future where this

12:21.040 --> 12:30.500
will stop or you can imagine a present where you're not there for a little
while. To live inside your head and to forget the horror that surrounds you.

12:30.680 --> 12:40.580
That's a huge thing to be able to do, and a lot of people did it. It's
remarkable, it's miraculous. but that's what a human being is a miraculous

12:40.580 --> 12:52.340
animal in the history of the world who's able to survive okay I just have a
couple more here in reading your work I obviously have picked up your admiration

12:52.340 --> 13:02.420
for George Bernard Shaw but I've never heard a statement or read a statement
from you as to why you admire him so much well my god he is of all the writers

13:02.420 --> 13:14.400
of our time just about at least on the when you think of Irish-English
literature for the theater, he is the idea writer of all idea writers, he and G

13:14.400 --> 13:25.340
.K. Chesterton and a few others, but he sort of outraces and outpaces everyone.
You name a subject, and he just pretty well wrote about it 70 years ago, 100

13:25.340 --> 13:35.620
years ago, 90 years ago. He was interested in theology. He was interested in
machinery. He was interested in the future. He was interested in biology. He had

13:35.620 --> 13:49.660
a far-ranging curiosity about mankind and the future of mankind. So he wrote
science fiction as well as doing theological studies and great characters from

13:50.220 --> 14:06.320
history like Saint John. I'm so sorry that I never had a chance to get to Europe
while he was still alive. Okay, this is sort of a strange question, but if you

14:06.320 --> 14:14.360
don't like to answer it you won't have to, but what books would you pick to, or
what books or authors would you think you'd pick to educate a young person from?

14:15.060 --> 14:26.320
Well, I would recommend George Bernard Shaw. As soon as someone was old enough,
I don't think you can give Shaw to children. nor can you give him to kids in

14:26.320 --> 14:38.860
high school. But as soon as people get into college, then I would bring Shaw out
and give them a complete education in ideas and how to think. And at the lower

14:38.860 --> 14:51.760
level, I'd imagine I would start them with Jules Verne and H.G. Wells, the
Science Fiction writers, because kids really are interested in ideas. and it's

14:51.760 --> 15:03.420
very playful. It's wonderful to have an interest in such things. And that's the
reason why science fiction during the last few years have been so popular in the

15:03.420 --> 15:13.480
high schools, in the junior high schools. The kids recognize that these fictions
deal with very real problems that must be solved, and you have the fun of

15:13.480 --> 15:15.760
playing with those toys inside your head.

